<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-254  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 254.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Nov 27 1989 v3 n48 p8(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Vendor queries stall VA automation plan; project will automate,integrate office operations nationwide. (the Department ofVeteran's Affairs' National Office Automation-Veteran'sAdministration contract)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Bids for the $298 million Department of Veterans Affairs' NationalOffice Automation-Veteran's Administration (Noava) contract willbe accepted until Dec 14, 1990, one month later than scheduled, asa result of questions from contractors about the procurement.andO;Noava will automate and integrate the operations of the VA'soffices throughout the US; it will last 10 years, does not specifya quantity or deliver, and will be mandatory for all agencyoffices.andP;  The 600-page RFP generated many questions from vendors,and the VA wished to give contractors the time needed to analyzethe complex and expensive project.andP;  There are 172 VA hospitals,making it the largest medical complex in the world, and thecontract entails many special requirements.andP;  Wang Laboratories isconsidered one of the leading contenders for the award; Wang wonan $82 million 10-year VA automation contract in 1984.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government ContractsOffice AutomationHospitalHealth CareNational GovernmentCompetitive BiddingUnited States. Department of Veterans Affairs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>